{{Other people|Gaultier}}
'''Jules de Gaultier''' (born in 1858 in Paris, died in 1942 in [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]]), born '''Jules Achille de Gaultier de Laguionie''', was a [[France|French]] [[philosopher]] and essayist. He was a contributor to ''Mercure de France'' and one of the chief advocates of "[[nietzscheism]]" in vogue in the literary circles of the day. He was known especially for his theory of "[[bovarysme]]" (the name taken from Flaubert's novel), by which he meant the continual need of humans to invent themselves, to lie to themselves. His books include ''De Kant à Nietzsche'' (1900) and ''Le Bovarysme, essai sur le pouvoir d'imaginer'' (1902).<ref>Le Petit Robert 2, S.E.P.R.E.T. (Paris), 1975.</ref>

